{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518234"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:02:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12903"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12903"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.09,0.74,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38450"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5341"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22905"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"286"},{"type":"tags","id":"1727"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"8855"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44001"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a six month history of progressively worsening dryness in her eyes. She describes a constant feeling of \u0022sand\u0022 in her eyes. Along with that she also has mild discomfort and difficulty swallowing dry foods. She feels fatigued when climbing stairs, and often has knee pain with this. She also feels her hands are weaker and more tender generally, particularly when working at her desk. Occasionally, she has numbness in her hands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her conjunctiva appears dry. She has no rash. On examination of her joints, her knees have no effusions. She has no active synovitis of her wrists or metacarpophalangeal joints. Her radial, median and ulnar nerve function are intact bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer Schirmer test is positive. Her antinuclear antibody (ANA) test is positive with a speckled pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical fluorometholone","Topical pilocarpine","Artificial tears","Topical diclofenac","Topical cyclosporin A (CyA)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this patient is Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome. This is supported by her sicca symptoms (dryness in the mouth and eyes), along with additional features such as arthralgia, fatigue, and positive antinuclear antibody (ANA) with a speckled pattern. Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome is a chronic autoimmune disorder characterized by lymphocytic infiltration of exocrine glands, primarily affecting the salivary and lacrimal glands. Topical lubricants such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eartificial tears\u003C/strong\u003E are the first-line treatment option. Topical lubricants are generally well-tolerated and can be used long-term to manage the chronic symptoms of Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome. Using gustatory stimulants (sugar-free acidic candies, lozenges, xylitol) and/or mechanical stimulants (sugar-free chewing gum) are also potential adjunctive treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical pilocarpine\u003C/strong\u003E (a muscarinic agonist) can be considered in patients with moderate glandular dysfunction. This acts by pharmacological stimulation of tear production and can be used as an adjunctive treatment along with artificial tears. It is not the first-line treatment option and is not used long-term.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical diclofenac\u003C/strong\u003E (an NSAID) is sometimes used as a short-term treatment option for patients with sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome. It is not first-line and cannot be used long-term because of side effects such as ulcers and keratopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical corticosteroids such as \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical fluorometholone \u003C/strong\u003Ecan sometimes be prescribed in Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome for the short term only. They are used particularly when there is systemic involvement or significant organ inflammation. They are also not used for long-term because of their many side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical cyclosporin A (CyA) \u003C/strong\u003Ecan sometimes be used in patients with refractory or severe ocular dryness that requires multiple courses of topical corticosteroids, but the evidence for its use is weak and thus it is not used as a first-line treatment option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lubricants such as artificial tears are the first-line and safest long-term treatment option for patients with Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome."],"references":["Ramos-Casals M, Brito-Zer\u00f3n P, Bombardieri S, et al. EULAR recommendations for the management of Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome with topical and systemic therapies. Ann Rheum Dis. 2020;79(1):3-18. doi:10.1136/annrheumdis-2019-216114"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12903"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"i